\begin_layout Subsection*
Bernoulli odometer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual: the Bernoulli space 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 endowed with the weak product topology and thus a Borel space with the
 usual Borel measure.
 The odometer is the transition function that increments by one...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\left(b_{k}\right)=\left(b_{0},b_{1},\cdots\right)\in B$
\end_inset

 be a string of bits.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 be the index of the first bit that is not one.
 Then define the transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $T:B\to B$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[T\left(b\right)\right]_{k}=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }k<l\left(b\right)\\
1 & \mbox{ if }k=l\left(b\right)\\
b_{k} & \mbox{ if }k>l\left(b\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Note that this is a Borel map, in that it maps Borel sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to other Borel sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be visualized in the usual fashion.
 Let binary strings be represented by real numbers as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left(b\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}b_{k}2^{-k-1}
\]

\end_inset

This mapping is surjective, not injective, as every dyadic ratonal comes
 from two distinct strings.
 But, as usual we ignore the difference; the set of dyadic rationals is
 of measure zero, and we write 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-1}$
\end_inset

 in a care-free manner.
 This is adequate for visualization.
 In particular, this allows 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $T=x\circ T\circ x^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
