\begin_layout Subsection*
Uniform Ornstein odometer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify things, first consider the uniform Ornstein odometer.
 This is the odometer, dettached from the usual type-III measure that goes
 with it.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{n}=\left\{ 0,1,2,\cdots,n-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the usual cyclic group.
 Define the uniform Ornstein odometer space as the infinite Cartesian product
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\mathbb{Z}_{2}\times\mathbb{Z}_{3}\times\mathbb{Z}_{4}\times\cdots
\]

\end_inset

As before, let 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\left(b_{k}\right)=\left(b_{0},b_{1},\cdots\right)\in A$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of symbols drawn from the product space.
 The odometer transition function is defined in a similar fashion as before.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(b\right)$
\end_inset

 be the index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 that is not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $T:A\to A$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[T\left(b\right)\right]_{k}=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }k<l\left(b\right)\\
b_{k}+1 & \mbox{ if }k=l\left(b\right)\\
b_{k} & \mbox{ if }k>l\left(b\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Again, it is a Borel map, mapping Borel sets to Borel sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Points in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can again be mapped to points in the real unit interval, and so this odometer
 can be visualized.
 The mapping is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\left(b\right)=\frac{b_{0}}{2}+\frac{b_{1}}{6}+\frac{b_{2}}{24}+\cdots=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{\left(k+2\right)!}
\]

\end_inset

and, as before, this induces a mapping on the real unit interval.
 Visually, it resembles the Bernoulli odometer:
